    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Harp zithers of western central Africa, made of a stalk of raffia palm from the surface of which from three to five strings are detached and supported above the string bearer by a central, vertical, notched bridge; from one to six gourd resonators are attached to the back of the string bearer. They are played by plucking.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Arpas cítaras del centro de Africa Occidental, hechas de un tallo de palmera de rafia desde cuya superficie se separan de tres a cinco cuerdas que se sujetan encima del portador de cuerdas mediante un puente vertical central, con muescas; de uno a seis resonadores de calabaza se fijan detrás del portador de cuerdas. Estos instrumentos se tocan punteándolos.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Harpciters met 3-5 snaren losgemaakt uit het oppervlak van een raffiapalmstengel, boven de snarenhouder ondersteund door een centrale, verticale, ingekerfde kam; 1-6 klankbodems van kalebas aan de achterkant van de snarenhouder; bespeeld door er op te tokkelen; West Centraal-Afrika.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052453/Algemene muziekencyclopedie (1961)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>指中非西部的一種齊特琴，由酒椰棕櫚的莖製成，具三到五根琴弦，琴弦與琴面分離，位在琴弦支撐物正上方，由位居中間且具刻痕的垂直琴橋支撐。一至六個葫蘆製共鳴箱於琴弦支撐物後方，以撥弦的方式演奏。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Harfenzither des westlichen Zentralafrika, hergestellt aus einem Stängel der Raphia-Palme, aus deren Epidermis zwischen drei und fünf Saiten herausgetrennt sind, die über dem Saitenträger von einem mittigen, vertikalen, gekerbten Steg gestützt werden; an der Rückseite des Saitenträgers sind zwischen einem und sechs Kalebassen als Resonatoren angebracht. Die Mvet wird gezupft.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
